No, apparently not. The creature hissed and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite his size, Thassalin was agile enough to avoid it, but Nyssi let out a scream as she nearly lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
“HOW CAN WE KILL HER?”, Nyssi shouted.
“TARGET THEIR HEADS!”
“THAT WILL BE DIFFICULT!”
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but it became slightly panicked when it was hit by a fire blast from behind. It hadn't realized it wasn't alone anymore. It became even more panicked as Thassalin slowed down and then swung his tail against its head, throwing it off course.
Growling and hissing, it flew upwards and spat into the air. All suddenly became dark, as if the monster had sucked the light from the sky and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he suddenly could no longer see anything, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree branches before finally crashing into an open clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and shot directly at him, dragging the black cloud with it.
“Kayel!” Tenuk shouted as he slid out of the cloud and began circling, trying to spy on Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. “What should we do now? Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?”
Below, Nyssi struggled to stand up. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, supernatural healing powers were already starting to work. Unfortunately, this did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi tried her best to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters ahead. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in this shadow, something was screaming and screeching.
A terrifying armored tail crashed next to Nyssi on the ground, knocking her down. But she noticed that the tail was swinging wildly and not attempting to hit her deliberately. The beast, or what little Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and swiped with its claws at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, pierced the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gun shot crashed through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsing on the ground and remaining motionless. The darkness around them dissipated, and they saw what had happened: Standing on the beast was Kayel, who was panting heavily and holding his gun tightly.
“That was probably… The craziest shadow leap I've ever made… Thanto kat'olon…” Kayel gasped for air. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy swirlled around his body. But as he spoke, the color returned to his armor, and his eyes took on their normal yellow hue.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He rarely used them because most found them eerie and quite terrifying. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could employ these powers in any kind of darkness. And judging by Kayel's behavior, it seemed he was equally surprised.
“Are you okay?” Nyssi blurted out.
“Yes, I'm fine. I killed something; I'll be back to normal soon.” Kayel examined his work while Tenuk flew down, landed beside him, and reverted to his normal spastic form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was raven black and slimy, but the slime stayed firmly attached to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns stood out from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell they were dealing with, something screamed and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it didn't make it to them because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to slide to a stop in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi wasn't taking any chances. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without hesitation at its head, and the creature died right there on the spot.
"Oops…", murmured Retvik from the driver's seat before clumsily turning off the engine and stepping out of the truck. "Uh, that was actually not intentional. Are you all okay?"
"You missed all the action," complained Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You just left me behind. I came as fast as I could…", sighed Retvik. "May I ask what those awful creatures are?"
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had recovered. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
“YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIDONS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WERE ESCAPING AS THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS.”
“You mean the terrible god-monster-being that we… helped kill?” stammered Tenuk.
“YES. EXACTLY THAT. PERHAPS THERE ARE MORE. BUT I COULD NOT SHOOT INTO THE HEAD. I HAVE NO FIREARM. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, OR?“ Thassalin limped over to Kayel and patted him on the head. “THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. ONLY NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO CAPABLE OF KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSES.”
“Ahem… thank you… I think…”, shrugged Kayel. “So, are we done here then?”
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the now definitely dead creatures. Then she picked up her favorite weapon, the decorated god-slayer knife, and began cutting off one of the creature's horns. After that, she moved on to the second one. But just as Nyssi finished, the creatures suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ash in an instant. The same happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
“So, this is both practical and impractical…,” sighed Nyssi. “But at least I have the photos, hopefully.”
